Drexel University is also known for creating the world's first Engineering Degree in [[Appropriate Technology]].<ref>{{Cite web| date = 1 June 2007| url =http://www.drexel.edu/catalog/ug/coe/appropriate-index.htm| title = Appropriate Technology| publisher= Drexel University Catalog| accessdate =3 September 2007 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090123154051/http://www.drexel.edu/catalog/ug/coe/appropriate-index.htm |archivedate=23 January 2009}}</ref> Drexel is also one of only 17 U.S. universities to offer a Bachelors in Architectural Engineering, and only one of five private institutions to do so.<ref>http://www.univsource.com/architectural.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.drexel.edu/academics/coe/cae/ugarch.asp |title=Drexel University College of Engineering: Architectural Engineering}}</ref>

===The Drexel Engineering Curriculum (tDEC)===
The 2006 edition of [[U.S. News]] ranks the undergraduate engineering program #57 in the country and the 2007 edition of graduate schools ranks the graduate program #61. The 2008 edition ranks the University Engineering Program at #55 and in the 2009 US News Ranking, the university has moved up to the #52 position.

The engineering curriculum used by the school was originally called E4 (Enhanced Educational Experience for Engineers) which was established in 1986<ref name="tdec">{{Cite news|date=10 February 2006|title=CoE plans to revamp entire engineering curriculum |url=http://media.www.thetriangle.org/media/storage/paper689/news/2006/02/10/News/Coe-Plans.To.Revamp.Entire.Engineering.Curriculum-1608638-page2.shtml |first=Daniel |last=Silva |publisher=The Triangle |accessdate=11 December 2007 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20101209032607/http://media.www.thetriangle.org/media/storage/paper689/news/2006/02/10/News/Coe-Plans.To.Revamp.Entire.Engineering.Curriculum-1608638-page2.shtml |archivedate=9 December 2010}}</ref> and funded in part by the Engineering Directorate of the [[National Science Foundation]].<ref name="tdec2">{{Cite journal| last = Warnock | first = Scott | author2 = Andrew J. McCann | title = Structured, Online Evaluations and the First-Year Design Process | journal = Learning Technology | volume = 6 | issue = 4 | publisher = IEEE Computer Society | month= October | year= 2004 | url = http://lttf.ieee.org/learn_tech/issues/october2004/index.html | accessdate =11 December 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070711052015/http://lttf.ieee.org/learn_tech/issues/october2004/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 11 July 2007}}</ref> In 1988 the program evolved into tDEC (the Drexel Engineering Curriculum)<ref name="tdec2" /> which is composed of two full years of rigorous core engineering courses which encompass the freshman and sophomore years of the engineering student. The College of Engineering hasn't used the tDEC curriculum since approximately 2005.

===Co-op program===
Branded as "the Ultimate Internship",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.library.drexel.edu/displays/items/show/199 |title=The Ultimate Internship |at=Drexel University Archives Digital Collections, Item #199 |accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref> Drexel's longstanding cooperative-education or "co-op" program is one of the largest and oldest in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.drexel.edu/scdc/coop/about/index.html |title=Drexel Co-op |publisher=Drexel University}}</ref> Drexel has a fully [[internet]]-based job database, where students can submit résumés and request interviews with any of the thousands of companies that offer positions. Students also have the option of obtaining an internship via independent search. A student graduating from Drexel's 5-year degree program typically has a total of 18 months of internship with up to three different companies. The majority of Co-ops are paid, averaging $15,912 per 6-month period, however this figure changes with major.<ref name="co-op">{{Cite web| year= 2006| url =http://www.drexel.edu/em/ug/coop/employers.html| title =Drexel Co-op Employers| publisher =Drexel University| accessdate =24 March 2006 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060515002401/http://www.drexel.edu/em/ug/coop/employers.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 15 May 2006}}</ref> The working experience highly pays off as one third of Drexel graduates are offered full-time positions by their Co-op employers right after graduation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/drexel-university-3256 |title=Drexel Co-op |publisher=US News and World Reports}}</ref>

===Research===
Drexel's knowledge community of researchers and scholars are socially, professionally and intellectually diverse. Many of Drexel's faculty and staff are seasoned practitioners with strong academic and private sector experiences. Drexel's intellectual climate is creative, flexible and responsive to change, thereby facilitating the emergence of innovative new lines of inquiry and exploration and seeding new avenues of creative expression. Research Centers and Institutes at Drexel include:

