===Online education===
Drexel has offered online degrees since 1996 and in 2002 created its online education program, Drexel University Online.<ref name="DOnline">{{Cite news|date=19 August 2007 |title=A coast-to-coast vision – Drexel's Papadakis has driven growth |first=Kathy |last=Boccella |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |page=A01 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=About Drexel University Online |url=http://www.drexel.com/corporate/drexelonline.aspx |publisher=Drexel Online |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> It is run by Drexel eLearning, Inc. (DeL), a wholly owned for-profit subsidiary of Drexel University.<ref>{{Cite web|title=About Drexel University Online |url=http://www.drexel.com/corporate/careers.aspx |publisher=Drexel Online |accessdate=20 May 2013}}</ref> Drexel Online maintains the same level of accreditation by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]; other colleges accredited by this body include Cornell, Penn, and NYU.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Drexel Online Accreditations & National Rankings |url=http://www.drexel.com/accreditation.aspx |publisher=Drexel Online |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref>

In September 2010, Drexel University Online received the Sloan-C award for institution-wide excellence in online education indicating that it had exceptional programs of "demonstrably high quality" at the regional and national levels and across disciplines.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sloan Consortium Honors Drexel with Excellence in Online Education Award |url=http://www.drexel.edu/news/headlines/sloan-consortium-honors-drexel-with-excellence-in-online-education-award.aspx |publisher=Drexel University|accessdate=16 February 2011}}</ref> Drexel University Online has won the 2008 [[United States Distance Learning Association]]'s Best Practices Awards for Distance Learning Programming.<ref>{{Cite web|year=2008 |title=USDLA Distance Learning Awards - 2008 |url=http://www.usdla.org/index.php?cid=118 |publisher=United states Distance Learning Association |accessdate=1 September 2010 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100221125027/http://www.usdla.org/index.php?cid=118 |archivedate=21 February 2010}}</ref> In 2007 the online education program had a revenue of $40 million,<ref name="DOnline" /> and in 2010 had 8,000 students and offered almost 90 total certificates, undergraduate, and graduate degrees.<ref name="DOnline2">{{Cite news|date=23 April 2010 |title=Drexel set to launch local media campaign to tout online classes |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sacramento/stories/2010/04/26/story7.html |work=Sacramento Business Journal |first=Kelly |last=Johnson |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref>

