==Student lore and traditions==

Tradition suggests that rubbing the toe of the [[Bronze sculpture|bronze]] "Waterboy" [[statue]] located in the Main Building atrium can result in receiving good grades in exams. Although the rest of the bronze statue has developed a dark brown [[patina]] over the years, the toe has remained highly polished and shines like new.<ref name="dragon" />

The Flame of Knowledge, a fountain once located in the main quad (relocated to the area in front of North Hall in early 2007), used to be known as the "Drexel Shaft" in the late 70s and early 80s,<ref>{{cite web |title=Return of the Red-Eye (Satire) |publisher=The Triangle |at=Drexel University Archives Digital Collections, Item #207 |url= http://archives.library.drexel.edu/displays/items/show/207 | accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref> however the name outgrew the landmark.<ref>{{Cite web|title=North Hall Fountain - Drexel university|url= http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM2T64 |publisher=WayMarking |accessdate=11 June 2008}}</ref> The "Drexel Shaft" now refers to the Penn Coach Yard chimney, the large smoke stack structure which was located east of 32nd street. Unresponsive treatment by the administration has been termed the "Drexel Shaft" by students.<ref>{{Cite news|date=27 October 1997 |title=Not Dragon His Feet Business-like Drexel Prez Making Swift Changes |publisher=''Philadelphia Daily News''}}</ref> The smoke stack was demolished on 15 November 2009, a long-anticipated event which the students hope will improve the overall aesthetics of the university.<ref>{{Cite news|date=6 November 2009 |title='Drexel Shaft' to be Imploded|url= http://media.www.thetriangle.org/media/storage/paper689/news/2009/11/06/News/drexel.Shaft.To.Be.Imploded-3825696.shtml|publisher=''The Triangle'' |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100806125321/http://media.www.thetriangle.org/media/storage/paper689/news/2009/11/06/News/drexel.Shaft.To.Be.Imploded-3825696.shtml |archivedate=6 August 2010}}</ref>

==In popular culture==
[[File:US Open Squash Championship 2011 Drexel University.jpg|thumb|The glass show court used at the 2011 US Open Squash Championships hosted by Drexel University at the [[Daskalakis Athletic Center]]]]
Drexel has appeared in news and television media several times. In 2006 Drexel served as the location for ABC Family's reality show "Back on Campus."<ref>{{Cite web|title=Back on Campus |url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0791272/ |publisher=IMDB |accessdate=12 December 2007}}</ref> Also in that year the Epsilon Zeta chapter of [[Delta Zeta]] won ABC Daytime's Summer of Fun contest. As a result the sorority was featured in national television spots for a week and also hosted an ABC party on campus which was attended by cast members from [[General Hospital]] and [[All My Children]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=6 March 2006 |title=Drexel Delta Zeta Chapter Wins ABC Campus Invasion Contest |url=http://www.drexel.edu/univrel/digest/archive/030606/index.html |publisher=Drexel Daily Digest |accessdate=29 November 2007}}</ref>

John Langdon, adjunct professor in the Antoinette Westphal College of Media Arts & Design, created the ambigram featured on the cover of Dan Brown's Angels & Demons and a number of other ambigrams were served as the central focus of the book and film. It is believed Prof. Langdon was the inspiration for the name of the lead character played by Tom Hanks in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|title=John Langdon |url=http://www.drexel.edu/westphal/contact/directory/LangdonJohn/ |publisher=Drexel |accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref>

In 2007 Drexel was the host of the 2008 Democratic Presidential candidate debate in Philadelphia, televised by [[MSNBC]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=23 October 2007 |title=Drexel Univ. To Host Presidential Debate |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/10/24/politics/uwire/main3400948.shtml |first=LeAnne |last= Matlach| publisher=CBS |accessdate=24 June 2008}}</ref> In 2008 from 10 January to the 13th Drexel hosted the US Table Tennis Olympic Trials.<ref>{{Cite web|month=August | year=2007 |title=Phila. will host '08 table tennis trials |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_kmtpi/is_200708/ai_n19404303 |publisher=The Philadelphia Inquirer |accessdate=12 December 2007}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=City of Brotherly Love to Host 2008 U.S. Olympic Team Trials for Table Tennis, January 10&ndash;13 |url=http://www.usatt.org/news1/2008_team_trials_drexel.shtml |publisher=USA Table Tennis |accessdate=15 January 2008}}</ref> Drexel University hosted the 2011 U.S. Open Squash Championships from  1–6 October 2011 as well as the 2012 U.S. Open Squash Championships from 4–12 October 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Drexel to Host 2011 U.S. Open Squash Championships |url=http://www.drexeldragons.com/news/2011/1/24/GEN_0124110942.aspx?path=gen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=U.S. Open Squash returns to the DAC |url=http://www.drexeldragons.com/news/2012/10/3/MSQ_1003120222.aspx?path=msq}}</ref>

==Alumni==
{{Main|List of Drexel University alumni}}

Since its founding the university has graduated over 100,000 alumni.<ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |title=Debate at Drexel: About Drexel University |url=http://www.drexel.edu/debate/drexel.asp |publisher=Drexel University|accessdate=31 December 2009 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090123154134/http://www.drexel.edu/debate/drexel.asp |archivedate=2 December 2011}}</ref> Certificate-earning alumni such as artist [[Violet Oakley]] and illustrator [[Frank Schoonover]] reflect the early emphasis on art as part of the university's curriculum. With [[World War II]], the university's technical programs swelled, and as a result Drexel graduated alumni such as [[Paul Baran]], one of the founding fathers of the Internet and one of the inventors of the [[packet switching]] network, and [[Norman Joseph Woodland]] the inventor of [[barcode]] technology. In addition to its emphasis on technology Drexel has graduated several notable athletes such as [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) basketball players [[Michael Anderson (basketball)|Michael Anderson]] and [[Malik Rose]], and several notable business people such as [[Raj Gupta]], former President and [[Chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Rohm and Haas]], and [[Kenneth C. Dahlberg]], former CEO of [[Science Applications International Corporation]] (SAIC).

In 1991, the university's centennial anniversary, Drexel created an association called the Drexel 100, for alumni who have demonstrated excellence work, philanthropy, or public service. After the creation of the association 100 alumni were inducted in 1992 and since then the induction process has been on a biennial basis. In 2006 164 total alumni had been inducted into the association.<ref name="drexel100">{{Cite journal|title=The Drexel 100|newspaper=Drexel Blue & Gold |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=24&ndash;25 |date=15 June 2006|url=http://www.drexel.edu/univrel/new/alumnimagazine/winter_2006.pdf |format=PDF|accessdate=12 January 2008}}</ref>

==Awards==
Drexel University created the annual $100,000 Anthony J. Drexel Exceptional Achievement Award to recognize a faculty member from a U.S. institution whose work transforms both research and the society it serves. The first recipient was bioengineer [[James Collins (Boston University)|James J. Collins]] of Boston University and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute.<ref>http://www.drexel.edu/achievement/</ref>

In 2004, in conjunction with [[BAYADA Home Health Care]], Drexel University's College of Nursing and Health Professions created the BAYADA Award for Technological Innovation in Nursing Education and Practice. The award honors nursing educators and practicing nurses whose innovation leads to improved patient care or improved nursing education.<ref>{{cite web|title=About BAYADA Awards|url=http://www.drexel.edu/cnhp/newsEvents/events/BayadaAwards/|publisher=drexel.edu|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>

